# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carbon-monoxide-poisoning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/14th-cmas-underwater-photography-world-championship] The **14th CMAS Underwater Photography World Championship** was held from April 9 – 14, 2013 in Cuba at Cayo Largo.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/14th-cmas-underwater-photography-world-championship] **David Barrio** of Spain was announced as the CMAS World Champion in underwater photography for 2013 and received the gold medal while runners-up **Stefano Proakis** and **Michele Davino** both representing Italy respectively received the silver and bronze medals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/14th-cmas-underwater-photography-world-championship] The Federacion Cubana de Actividades Subacuaticuas (English: *Cuban Federation of Underwater Activities*) (FCAS) hosted the championship on behalf of the Confédération Mondiale des Activités Subaquatiques (CMAS) with assistance from the Ministry of Tourism of Cuba (MINTUR).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/14th-cmas-underwater-photography-world-championship] The following countries sent teams with a total of 78 competitors to compete - Argentina, Belgium, Brazil, Cuba, Croatia, Denmark, France, Germany, Italy, Mexico, Norway, Portugal, Spain, Slovenia, South Korea, Sweden, the Netherlands and Turkey.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/14th-cmas-underwater-photography-world-championship] The following photographic categories were used for this championship: fish, close-up with a theme, close-up (without a theme), wide angle (without diver) and wide angle with diver.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The **1973 Mount Gambier cave diving accident** was a scuba diving incident on 28 May 1973 at a flooded sinkhole known as "The Shaft" near Mount Gambier in South Australia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The incident claimed the lives of four recreational scuba divers: siblings Stephen L. and Christine M.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The four divers explored beyond their own planned limits, without the use of a guideline, and subsequently became lost, eventually exhausting their breathing air and drowning, with their bodies all recovered over the next year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] To date, they are the only known fatalities at the site.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Four other divers from the same group survived.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The incident was influential in the restriction of access to cave diving venues in Australia, the formation of the Cave Divers Association of Australia later that year, and the development of the South Australian Police Underwater Recovery Squad.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The hole was later opened up to about 1 metre (3.3 ft) diameter for exploration access.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] In the mid-1960s a local diver climbed down the rain-enlarged 0.8 metres (2.6 ft) opening into the cave’s 17-metre (56 ft) wide lake chamber and made the first descent to a depth of about 21 metres (69 ft).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The cave is one of several deep solution features in porous limestone in this part of south Australia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The main chamber is about 140 metres (460 ft) long and 80 metres (260 ft) wide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Water level is about 7 metres (23 ft) below ground level, and the hole is considerably wider at this point.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] A rock pile directly under the surface opening rises to a minimum depth of about 36 metres (118 ft).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] A tunnel extends to the northwest to a depth of about 80 metres (260 ft), and another to the east reaches a maximum depth of 124 metres (407 ft).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Because of the size of the hole and the height of the drop, divers and equipment are lowered into the chamber separately using a hoist system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The name is claimed to be derived from the bright shaft of sunlight which penetrates through the entrance to the depths on a sunny day.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The first reasonably accurate map of the cavern was made in 1984 after the newly formed CDAA Research Group made mapping and photographic dives showing the chamber to be roughly oval in shape.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] There was another exploration in June 1992, but the deepest sections were surveyed and mapped in 2002/03.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The eastern tunnel is obstructed by restrictions at about 57 metres (187 ft) and continues downwards to 124 metres (407 ft) before becoming horizontal, and further access is blocked by a rock pile.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Despite knowing their maximum depths, however, the total lengths of the northwest and southwest tunnels are unknown, and they may extend as far as the southern shores as part of the intricate freshwater-drainage system flowing through the mountains in the area.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The Shaft is on private land and is restricted to divers accredited with the CDAA.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] On 26 May 1973, a group of nine divers arrived at Mount Gambier in South Australia with the intention of cave diving at "The Shaft," a 3 feet (0.91 m) wide sinkhole opening leading to a large underwater cavern, famous among divers for its clear water and interesting internal structure.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Smith were the eight divers intending to venture into the cave; a ninth group member, Joan Harper, had decided she would not be diving, and would instead remain beside the sinkhole, preparing hot soup and assisting the group in other ways.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The day prior to the accident, the group signed the guestbook at the farmhouse of B.V.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Ashby, and completed a successful dive at the sinkhole, extending a shot line approximately 150 feet (46 m) into the water and reaching the primary point of interest known as the "rock pile", a central pile of limestone rubble about 40 meters directly below the sinkhole entrance.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] They briefly explored the perimeter of the rock pile before surfacing.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] With their shot line already in place, the group planned to return the next morning and continue exploring the cavern.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The group arrived at the sinkhole on the morning of 28 May after refilling their 72 cubic feet (2.0 m3) cylinders at Mount Gambier, and quickly descended to the rock pile.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Reports from the divers indicate that they had not planned to explore beyond "the edge", a narrow and downward-sloping continuation of the cave on one side of the main chamber, far from the natural light shaft provided by the sinkhole opening.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Even at the depths of the rock pile perimeter, the effects of narcosis would have been significant, which may have already been impacting the judgement of the divers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] While the initial descent went smoothly, the eight divers neglected several recognised safety procedures early in the dive.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The shot line did not extend all the way to the cavern floor, and was not equipped with extra air tanks, nor were the divers prepared with adequate air management strategies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The group had not established specific diving partners, and they did not use any form of safety guide line; Glen Millott later stated they did not use safety lines because eight separate lines in such a confined space would have created a dangerous situation for the divers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Robert Smith, who had dived at the sinkhole on eight previous occasions and established most of the dive plan, was not expecting the other members of the group to venture as far into the cave as they did.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Separate accounts from the four surviving divers were pieced together with the help of former Chief Superintendent Wallace B.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Budd to establish a timeline of what happened to the four victims.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] At the perimeter of the rock pile, Smith began to feel the effects of nitrogen narcosis.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] His depth gauge read approximately 180 feet (55 m).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] An experienced diver, familiar with the symptoms of narcosis, Smith signaled to his group that he was returning to the top of the rock pile.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The group signaled that they were going to continue exploring.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Smith stayed by the rock pile, circling it for around 8 minutes while searching for animal bones.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] He then saw the torch of Glen Millott returning from the direction the others had gone.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Glen Millott had been monitoring his air, and knew that he was out of time; he had attempted to tap Christine Millott on the arm and remind her that her time was also up, but the two were separated before he could.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Smith and Glen Millott met and surfaced together to find that Larry Reynolds had already returned from his dive.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Half a minute later, Peter Burr surfaced with almost no air left in his tank.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Knowing the others would have similarly low air supplies, Glen Millott quickly put on a spare tank and returned to the water.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] He descended to a depth of 225 feet (69 m), where the cliff began to drop off.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Significant amounts of silt had been disturbed, and the visibility had been reduced to nearly zero.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Glen Millott had no choice but to decompress and return to the surface.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] By the time he surfaced, an ambulance had arrived at the sinkhole.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Peter Burr returned to the cavern for one more look, but found nobody.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] By that point, the group was aware that they were looking for bodies, and not survivors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] At the end of the planned dive, upon turning around to return to the surface, the surviving divers saw Christine Millott and Gordon Roberts attempt to ascend quickly back to the rock pile.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] However, instead of ascending along the slope they went down, they swam straight up, possibly because they were worried their air would be exhausted soon.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The two divers swam directly upward into a dome in the ceiling which had no exit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Reynolds reported seeing their torches frantically searching for an exit before Roberts signaled back that they were lost.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] According to Reynolds, Christine Millott and Gordon Roberts looked "frightened." This was the last time the two were seen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Likely suffering from nitrogen narcosis, and surrounded in silt allowing minimal visibility, the two failed to find an exit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] They exhausted their air supply and drowned; their bodies were later found together below the ceiling dome they had failed to escape.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Reports suggest that Christine Millott and Gordon Roberts may have been holding each other, as they knew their death was imminent.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Further down and around the same time, one surviving diver says they witnessed a member of their group swimming strongly downward further into the cave.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] This was John Bockerman, who was likely under the effects of severe nitrogen narcosis, and may have been unaware that he was swimming to his death.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] His body was located about 20 feet (6.1 m) further from where he was last seen, and was at the greatest depth of the four victims.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Millott, may have been seen lost beneath the cave ceiling shortly before the surviving divers surfaced.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Although his torch and camera were found deep at the base of the rock pile, his body was found under an overhang at a depth of only 50 feet (15 m).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Compared with the other victims, little is known about Stephen L.'s final moments, but he was wearing a buoyancy vest, and because he was found under an overhang, it is likely that he was buoyant at the time of death.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] A search of the cave by the police Underwater Recovery Squad to a depth of 200 feet (61 m) was initiated on 29 May 1973, the day after the accident.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The search was brief, and no bodies were found.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The team was aware that they were underprepared for a dive in such conditions, and the operation was described by Chief Inspector Wallace Budd of the South-Eastern Division police headquarters in Mount Gambier as a "learn as you go exercise." A second attempt was made on 30 May, again unsuccessful.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The police search was ultimately postponed as the team sought Naval expertise on the dive, the training for which was expected to take several months.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The following January, the landowners permitted a television film crew, making a documentary on cave diving in the Lower South East, to enter the sinkhole.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Further inspection revealed that it was a body in a wetsuit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The team turned the light away immediately and surfaced together to report their findings.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] According to the crew, the body was not filmed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] On the morning of 23 January 1974, police arrived at the sinkhole and dove to a depth of 50 feet (15 m), where they found a body floating under a ledge against the sloped cavern roof.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The body was immediately towed out, and police divers continued searching to a depth of 180 feet (55 m), finding nothing else.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The body was initially only identifiable by the equipment it was wearing, and official identification required dental records.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The body was found to be that of Stephen L.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The landowners, growing increasingly uncomfortable with the remaining three bodies stuck on their property, approached an amateur diving team from Melbourne to begin recovery efforts.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] However, the police diving team was finalising their recovery preparations around the same time.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Trayner and a team of divers entered "The Shaft" equipped with substantially improved diving gear.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] At a depth of 185 feet (56 m), Trayner saw a body below him laying on its back.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] On further examination, he found a second body directly beneath it.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] These were the bodies of Christine Millott and Gordon Roberts.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] 20 feet (6.1 m) deeper, Trayner also located the body of John Bockerman beneath a rock ledge.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] He attempted to move the body into a more easily recoverable position, but abandoned the effort knowing he did not have sufficient air.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The next day, the divers attempted to return and recover the bodies, but did not succeed, and the effort was called off after the water became too murky.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Several more dives were attempted, but the bodies could not be relocated.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Finally, on the third day of diving, the bodies were found, and Christine Millott and Gordon Roberts were recovered from a depth of 195 feet (59 m) on 11 March 1974.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Attempts were made to recover Bockerman's body from a depth of 215 feet (66 m) the following morning, but the divers aborted the recovery because of the onset of nitrogen narcosis.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The divers were sent home for a month to recover from the extended efforts and to further train for the final body recovery, which was the most challenging because of its extreme depth and position.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The divers experienced significant narcosis during both days of diving, but their improved equipment and procedures ensured the operation went as planned, and John H.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Bockerman's body was recovered from the cave on 9 April 1974, 11 months and 11 days after the accident.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The cause of death in all four divers was found to be lack of air with terminal drowning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Embolism was also found to be unlikely from the accounts of the survivors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The coroner, Special Magistrate R.F.Stokes, concluded that the four divers overstayed their bottom time, ran out of air and died of hypoxia, the usual consequence of fatal drowning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The equipment used by the divers was typical of the era, and when inspected under forensically valid conditions was found to be of good quality and in good condition.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Of 16 cylinders inspected by the police, 14 were 72 cubic feet (2.0 m3) and two were 50 cubic feet (1.4 m3), connected as a twin set.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] At least some of the cylinders relied on a manually operated reserve valve to release the air intended as a safety margin, which was common at the time.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The cylinders had been brought to the site with air filled in Sydney, but some had been refilled at Mount Gambier after the first dive.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Air in the cylinders used by the survivors was found to be within relevant recommendations for breathing air for diving.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] A sample of air taken from the Mount Gambier compressor was analysed and also found to be within standards, and the compressor in good condition, with the intake clear of possible sources of contamination.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Following the accident, Robert Smith alleged that he experienced severe nitrogen narcosis at 180 feet (55 m) on the initial dive, but experienced no narcotic effects after grabbing a spare tank and returning to depth to search for the others.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] He also claimed to be experienced at diving to depths up to 300 feet (91 m) (on air) without experiencing notable narcotic effects.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The tank he took on the first dive had been filled at Mount Gambier, while the spare tank taken for his second dive to search for the missing divers had been filled back in Sydney.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Smith is quoted as saying there was "something wrong with the local air", and proceeded to claim that contamination during the filling of the cylinders at Mount Gambier may have been the cause of the four fatalities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Cant, was consulted regarding the accident and specifically tasked with the examination of the cylinders recovered from Smith and the rest of the party.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] After extensive examination, and laboratory tests on the cylinder contents he concluded that the allegations of impure air were "entirely without foundation".
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Dr Cant had previously expressed an opinion that the group had neglected a number of safety measures in the planning and execution of the dive, and that these factors ultimately led to the incident.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The limestone aquifer in the Mount Gambier area is up to 150 metres (490 ft) thick and is fed by rain.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Flow is from northwest to south east through the porous rock, to exit at springs on the coast such as Ewens Ponds.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Several sinkholes (cenotes) have formed in areas where large volumes of rock have dissolved and the roofs of the voids later collapsed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Parts of some of these sinkholes can be dived with direct access to the surface or with visible daylight – classified as cavern diving, while other parts are beyond daylight and are classified as cave diving.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] From the early 1960s divers began to dive The Shaft, the Black Hole, Kilsby sinkhole and Picanninnie Ponds, with divers coming in from Victoria and New South Wales.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Most of these dives were conducted in sight of natural daylight using standard open water equipment and techniques, including the typical single cylinder with J-valve reserve and no pressure gauge, single demand valve, a wetsuit and a weightbelt, but not often a buoyancy compensator.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Single low powered dive lights were used, and caving reels had not yet become available.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] A small minority of divers started exploring the dark zones of sinkholes and true caves, and experimented with equipment which was to develop into modern cave diving equipment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Some experiment with base-fed lifelines highlighted their limitations in true caves, while working satisfactorily in most sinkhole environments.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Consequently cave reels were developed from about 1968, allowing the laying of static temporary and permanent guideline by the diver.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Very few twin cylinders were in use, and mostly they were manifolded to a single outlet.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Redundant air supplies started to be introduced in the 1970s, but were resisted because of cost.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Octopus regulators became accepted as cave diving equipment around 1976, and as sinkhole diving equipment a few years later.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The "air-clear" water conditions experienced in the sinkholes and caves found in the Lower South East (now called the Limestone Coast) of South Australia (SA) have attracted many visiting divers, with the first cave and sinkhole dives taking place in the very late 1950s.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Until the mid-1980s divers generally used single diving cylinders, and homemade torches and reels, resulting in most of their explorations being limited.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Mixed-gas and rebreather technologies can now be used in many sites.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The area is usually known within the cave diving community as the *Mount Gambier region*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] It is estimated that about 8000 dives had been done in The Shaft by the time of the incident.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] (CDAA) in September 1973 and the closing of sinkholes to persons not assessed by the CDAA.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] The introduction of a testing program by the CDAA in 1974, which involved the assessment of prospective cave divers' cave diving ability, led to a reduced fatality rate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] In 1989, this testing system was replaced by a training system which consists of three levels of qualification – *Basic Cave*, *Cave Diver* and *Advanced Cave Diver*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Five further deaths have occurred in the region since 1974; two died at *Piccaninnie Ponds* in 1984, one person died at *Kilsbys Hole* in 2010, and two people died in separate incidents at *Tank Cave* in 2011 including noted cave diver Agnes Milowka.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] This incident had immediate and long term consequences for the South Australian Police Underwater Recovery Squad, which had been formed in 1957 with the purpose of underwater search and recovery of bodies, stolen property, and other evidence associated with crime.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1973-mount-gambier-cave-diving-accident] Additional training and improved equipment were considered necessary for the body search and recovery operations, which expanded the scope of their capacities and have been cited as a turning point in the history of the unit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] The **1992 cageless shark-diving expedition** was the world's first recorded intentionally cageless dive with great white sharks, contributing to a change in public opinions about the supposed ferocity of these animals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] The dive took place in January 1992, during the filming of the National Geographic documentary *Blue Wilderness*, at Dyer Island, South Africa.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] After 8-10 large Great White sharks had been kept around their boat for about 6 hours using chum and sea mammal flesh, four scuba divers carried out the world's first recorded dive amongst these animals without a safety cage, or any other protection, like chain-mail suits.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] The divers were Ron and Valerie Taylor, notable Australian film-makers and pioneers of underwater exploration, their friend George Askew, a South African diver and photographer, and Piet 'PJ' van der Walt, who had founded the South African cage-diving industry in 1988.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] The Taylors and Askew, recognised shark experts and authorities, were testing their hypothesis that these animals had a much fiercer reputation than they deserved.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Their hypothesis was based on many years of experiences with various types of shark, including face to face encounters underwater.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Askew postulated that, as they rely on stealth and surprise when attacking, Great Whites would be unlikely to attack if you were aware of their presence.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] He had two more articles on the same subject published in 1983 and 1991, and then went on to prove that point with the historic dive in 1992.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] After a long 20 minute wait, the divers had several timid encounters with the very cautious sharks and were never at any time challenged, nor made to feel uneasy.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] This ground-breaking "Underwater Everest" conquest, a huge leap forward in ocean exploration, strongly challenged the idea of the Great White as a "Mindless Monster" eating machine, and changed the way the world viewed sharks.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] The Taylors felt that the Australian sharks may have a slightly different disposition to South African ones, but as it is now known that Great Whites swim between South Africa and Australia, this is open to debate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] On two occasions many years before, they had released Great Whites trapped in wire ropes from cages without being harassed, despite touching the animals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Askew had encountered Great White Sharks several times previously over the years whilst spear-fishing.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] The first was in 1960, when meeting one was considered to mean certain death.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] This encounter was with a very gravid female who had come into a small cove to drop her pup/s.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] She was in such an advanced stage of pregnancy that her body was distorted, with her mouth actually facing forward above her hugely distended stomach.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] She was what is referred to as a "Drop-Gut".
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] In the animal world a mother is usually very protective and aggressive just before and just after giving birth, and yet this large Apex Predator showed no aggression towards him.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Because of this and similar encounters, and those of his colleagues, he became more interested in this question.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Just before the dive, Askew and Ron Taylor were kneeling on the dive platform a few centimetres above water, with their hands in the water filming.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Askew stood up and stepped back, and at that moment a four-metre Great White slid onto the platform and stopped 3 inches from his foot before sliding back, but made no attempt to snap or lunge at him.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] It would have taken his camera and arms, and maybe pulled him in if he had not got up.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Askew sees that incident as pure opportunism and not savagery.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] The Prototype 'Pod" Valerie is seen wearing during this dive was a dummy for continuity and afforded the divers no protection.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] That first close encounter dive demonstrated that Great Whites are not built only to devour people but are very curious and can be quite 'friendly'.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] This dive is directly responsible for the upsurge in Shark Tourism – especially free-diving (i.e.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] When existing and potential operators around the world learnt of the theory that the Great White was quite approachable and not likely to attack, it was hypothesised that the same applied to other dangerous sharks such as tiger sharks, bull sharks and oceanic whitetip sharks.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] This proved to be the case and shark tourism began to expand rapidly.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] It is now a multibillion-dollar a year industry, and has provided a lot of useful insights into sharks.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Since this dive some divers have attempted cageless dives with big sharks, even hitching rides on their dorsal fins and touching them underwater.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] However, such attempts are not recommended as sharks are still Apex Predators and very opportunistic.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] Although there have never been any serious incidents from free-swimming with Great Whites, the same cannot be said for other sharks.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/1992-cageless-shark-diving-expedition] There have been a number of fatalities and other injuries.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] On 14 December 2024, the bodies of 12 individuals were discovered in a quarters billet of an Indian restaurant in Gudauri, Georgia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The victims were employees of the restaurant, and included 11 Indian nationals and one Georgian citizen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It was the worst accident in the region since a helicopter crash in 2022, where eight people died.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In Gudauri, there was an Indian restaurant, *Havel*, where mostly Indian employees worked.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The restaurant was in the building on the first floor, while the workers had lodgings on the second floor.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The day before the accident, there was a storm in Gudauri that caused a power outage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In order to be able to heat the lodgings, electric generators using fuel oil were placed in a closed area near the rooms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Fumes from the generator caused carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The victims later felt nauseous from the carbon monoxide and were unable to escape.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] On the second day, the restaurant owner discovered the corpses.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The bodies showed no signs of violence, ruling out foul play.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In the accident 12 people were killed, all of whom were restaurant workers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Eleven of them had Indian citizenship, and one person was a 25-year-old Georgian woman who worked as a waitress in the restaurant.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The Indian citizens were natives of Punjab.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Most of the Indian victims recently moved to Georgia in search of employment opportunities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The incident quickly went viral on social media, where users expressed grief and outrage, particularly over potential lapses in safety standards.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2024-gudauri-carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Government officials and community leaders called for stricter enforcement of safety regulations regarding the use of power generators, while Indian diplomatic representatives coordinated with Georgian authorities to assist in repatriating the victims' remains.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The **2026 Dhekunu Kandu cave diving incident** was a cave diving incident that occurred on 14 May 2026 at the Dhekunu Kandu cave, also known as the Devana Kandu or Thinwana Kandu cave system, near Alimathaa Island, Vaavu Atoll in the Maldives.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The incident involved a team of Italian divers participating in a research and diving expedition aboard the liveaboard vessel *MV Duke of York*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The dive took place in a deep underwater cave environment at depths which exceeded standard recreational diving limits of 30 meters, and the group failed to surface as scheduled.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] It was the deadliest diving accident ever recorded in the Maldives.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The incident claimed the lives of the five Italian divers and a diver of the Maldives National Defense Force who was part of a search and recovery operation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] All victims were recovered; those found deepest in the cave were recovered by an international rescue team organized by the Divers Alert Network.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Dhekunu Kandu Cave, also known as Shark Cave locally, is located near Alimathaa Island in the Vaavu Atoll and is approximately 60 miles from the capital Malé.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The first chamber acts as the entrance, and it is at a depth of 55 - 58 meters below sea level.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] A 3-meter-wide tunnel connects the first to the second larger chamber.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The latter is completely dark and has a silt floor which, if stirred up, can significantly reduce visibility by causing a silt out.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Under normal conditions, no relevant currents have been reported by previous divers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] During the recovery operations, a new dead-end tunnel was discovered in the second chamber, located to the side of the entrance tunnel.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] This part of the cave had never been mapped before and was absent from all existing maps.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The maximum extent of the cave is 60 - 70 meters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The research team was composed of Monica Montefalcone, Giorgia Sommacal, Muriel Oddenino, and Federico Gualtieri.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Monica Montefalcone, 51, was a marine researcher and associate professor of Ecology at the University of Genoa.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] She worked for DISTAV, the university's Department of Earth, Environmental, and Life Sciences.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] She graduated with honours in Biological Sciences from the University of Milan.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] She conducted long term studies of the coastal habitat of the Maldives.She also extensively studied the aquatic plant *Posidonia oceanica* in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Since 2013, she was the scientific director of major research projects on the coral reefs of the Maldives.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Her daughter Giorgia Sommacal often accompanied her during exploration of coastal habitats.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Muriel Oddenino was a Marine biologist and ecologist and a research fellow at DISTAV.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] She was also a Professional Association of Diving Instructors certified divemaster and deep diver, as well as a Technical Diving International certified nitrox diver.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Federico Gualtieri was a diving instructor and had a master's degree in Marine Biology and Ecology.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] All four were aboard the *MV Duke of York*, along with a larger group of 20 Italians as part of a scientific research expedition (or "research cruise") which the University of Genoa had undertaken annually since 1997.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Diving operations aboard of the *MV Duke of York* were managed by vessel's captain and diving instructor Gianluca Benedetti.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] A lawyer for the Italian tour company that sold trips on the yacht, Albatros Top Boat, stated that the operator of the *MV Duke of York* was unaware that the research team intended to dive further than the recreational limits and that they would not have allowed it if they had known.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] As part of the scientific mission, three of the five divers were authorized by the Maldivian authorities to dive to depths of 50 meters, rather than the usual 30-meter limit for recreational diving in the Maldives.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] A Maldivian government spokesperson stated that Montefalcone's authorization did not specify any cave penetration.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Lawyers representing the family of Montefalcone expressed surprise that the University would be unaware of any activity taking place during the research expeditions, given their annual occurrence.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The divers dived on May 14th, 2026, approximately at 11:00 am.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The dive was expected to last about one hour.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] When the divers didn't resurface at 12:00 pm they began searching for them with their vessel.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Their dive vessel *MV Duke of York* notified the Maldivian authorities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The search for the missing began almost immediately but was stymied due to a weather warning in the area.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Maldivian authorities identified the Thinwana Kandu cave as the dive's objective and the presumed location of the missing divers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Search operations on May 16, 2026 consisted of eight local divers working in shifts to locate the missing divers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The Maldivian government initially deployed military divers to attempt the recovery of the bodies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Initial teams were able to identify the cave entrance, mark it, and penetrate the first chamber of the cave.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Benedetti's body was the first to be recovered, from a depth of 60 meters, as he was lying in the first chamber of the cave, close to the entrance.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] This recovery effort however was suspended after one of the military divers, Sergeant Major Mohamed Mahudhee, became ill during ascent and subsequently died of decompression sickness after being transferred to ADK Hospital in Malé.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] An international search and recovery mission was established by the Maldivian and Italian authorities, and DAN Europe.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] A team of Finnish technical divers, some of whom were involved in the recovery of the bodies from the 2014 Pluragrotta disaster including Sami Paakkarinen, Jenni Westerlund and Patrik Grönqvist, were summoned to perform the recovery.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Initially the recovery team could not find the missing bodies, and feared they may have been dragged back to open sea by currents and then dispersed in the ocean.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Subsequently, the technical divers identified a previously unmapped dead-end tunnel in the second chamber.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The four remaining bodies were all found inside this tunnel.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] On May 19th the team successfully recovered the bodies of Montefalcone and Gualtieri and their equipment, including action cameras.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The recovery team transported the two bodies from the spot where they were found to a depth of approximately 30 meters, where Maldivian divers completed the transfer to the surface.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The first body was attached to a transport rope and then twenty minutes later the second body was attached.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Nurse sharks were reported to be present during the recovery of the first two bodies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The bodies were then loaded onto Coast Guard vessels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The bodies of Sommacal and Oddenino were recovered on May 20th, 2026.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The recovery of the last two bodies was hampered temporarily when a tiger shark approached the scene briefly and then left.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] On May 20, 2026 Mohamed Hussain Shareef, the spokesperson, for the Maldivian authorities confirmed that the bodies would all be repatriated to Italy.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The body of Gianluca Benedetti was the first to be returned.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] On Saturday May 23, 2026 the remaining four divers landed at Malpensa Airport and were to be processed at the morgue for autopsies the following Monday at Sant'Antonio Abate Hospital in Gallarate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The examination of the bodies was being conducted by Luca Tajana from the University of Pavia's Institute of Forensic Medicine.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The autopsies were completed on May 26, 2026 and the Montefalcone family lawyer Giuseppe Pugliese stated that no injuries or trauma identified and that the cause of death would be determined by the toxicology.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Lack of correct equipment and training were reported as possible factors in the incident.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The investigation is under the jurisdiction of the Maldives, however the Rome Prosecutor's Office is also investigating for manslaughter.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Italian prosecutors have asked Maldivian authorities for access to equipment, cameras and documentation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] They also asked for access to items currently in custody in Malé including the GoPros, dive computers, and other equipment that were recovered by the recovery team.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Electronic equipment from the victims has already been taken by the Genoa Flying Squad as part of the investigation opened by Rome.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] This includes computers, emails, hard drives, tablets, mobile phones, and USB drives that were owned by the victims.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] They were brought to Italy by Stefano Venin who was a University of Genoa professor that was on the same expedition.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Grönqvist stated that the divers were only equipped with standard compressed air, two of the divers were only wearing bikinis with a neoprene jacket over them, two divers had thin long wetsuits.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] He noted that the divers did not utilize a guide line to mark their way out of the cave.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] He stated that their tanks would have lasted only ten minutes at the depth they were found at which was 60 meters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] He stated that in order for them to ascend they would have needed six hours to complete the decompression because of the gas they were using in their tanks.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] A preliminary assessment released by DAN Europe in collaboration with Maldivian authorities suggests that it is likely that the divers became disorientated within the cave system and were unable to find their way back out.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] DAN Europe advised that any further causes and circumstances that caused the incident would be determined by the police and investigative authorities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Due to the ongoing investigation, the Maldives has suspended the operating licence of the liveaboard vessel *Duke of York*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The operator of the *MV Duke of York* Abdul Muhsin Moosa stated that the vessel had permission for recreational dives and that he went over the 30 meter limit with the divers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] However, Mohamed Hussain Shareef stated that the reason the vessel was suspended was because they are required to have a dive school permit in order to carry out expeditions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] He stated that they did not have this permit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] In the aftermath of the accident, several cave diving experts called for stricter consideration of cave diving precautions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] In the Maldives, drafting began on a new law to impose stricter restrictions on technical wreck diving, including dives involving depths greater than the 30 meters recreational limit, or enclosed spaces such as wrecks and caves.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Technical wreck diving would require a permit that is limited to researchers and highly certified divers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] The legislation aims to introduce minimum standards of experience, safety, equipment, and oversight that would be required before a permit could be granted.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Mohamed Hussain Shareef has stated that they are already discussing how to create a legal framework to legalize technical diving in the Maldives.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] This would allow diving in the Maldives beyond its diving tourism which composes of most of its diving industry.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] On May 16, 2026 Sergeant Major Mohamed Mahudhee of the Maldivian Coast Guard was buried with military honors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] President Mohamed Muizzu was in attendance of his funeral.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] Italian President Sergio Mattarella recognized the bravery and professionalism of three Finnish divers who formed part of the recovery operation and by awarding them the Order of Merit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/2026-dhekunu-kandu-cave-diving-incident] President Mohamed Muizzu honored Maldives Police Service and the Maldives National Defence Force who participated in the operation and presented them certificates of appreciation for their contributions during at a ceremony in Bandaara Koshi.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The Chinese **8A4 class ROUV** is a remotely operated underwater vehicle (ROUV) used to perform various underwater tasks, ranging from oil platform service to salvage and rescue missions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The 8A4 is a member of a series of related ROUVs developed by the Shenyang Institute of Automation (SIA) in the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The predecessor to the 8A4 was the RECON-IV, an improved version of the American RECON-III.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The 8A4 itself is an upgraded version of the American AMETEK 2006, and the 7B8 is an improved version of the 8A4.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The 8A4's origins trace back to the RECON-IV ROUV.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] China has operated ROUVs to support its offshore oil and salvage operations since the 1980s, such as Hysub 10 ROUVs and Hysub 40 ROUVs supplied by the Canadian firm International Submarine Engineering in British Columbia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The Shanghai Salvage Bureau deployed Hysub 40 ROUVs and proved them to be a successful platform for offshore oil drilling, salvage, and rescue missions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] However, foreign-built ROUVs were too expensive for wide adoption by the People's Liberation Army Navy (PLAN).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] As a result, China decided to develop its version of ROUVs with similar capabilities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] One of the first Chinese-built ROUVs was the RECON-IV ROUV, which was developed jointly by the Shenyang Institute of Automation of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and Perry Oceanographic (later purchased by Lockheed Martin) of Riviera Beach, Florida.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The design was based on Perry Oceanography's RECON-III ROUV, and RECON-IV's development facilitated technology transfer between the two organizations.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The RECON-IV ROUV was adopted by the People's Liberation Army Navy for salvage and rescue operations.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] However, like earlier ROUVs, the RECON-IV was primarily designed for civilian operations, which limited military applications such as cutting through the specialized steel used in submarines, and opening valves on sinking vessels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The limitations of the civilian model and the needs of the People's Liberation Army Navy prompted a follow-up design.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] In the late 1980s, China organized a design team to develop a ROUV that meets the needs of military salvage and rescue operations while also being able to perform civilian tasks.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Team members included the 702nd Research Institute of the China Shipbuilding Industry Corporation (CSIC), the Shipbuilding Engineering Institute of Harbin Engineering University (HEU), and the Institute of Underwater Engineering of Shanghai Jiao Tong University (SHJTU).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Xu Huangnan (徐芑南), a professor of SHJTU, was named as the general designer of the 8A4 ROUV.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] He would go on to be the deputy general designer of Explorer AUV, as well as the general designer of other Chinese unmanned underwater vehicles, including Sea Dragon class ROUV, CR class AUV, and SJT class ROUV.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] To shorten the development time, the team decided to select a ROUV system available on the market whose performance was closest to the requirements and then improve it based on experience developing the RECON-IV ROUV.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The AMETEK 2006, an American ROUV used to support offshore oil drilling operations, met both of these criteria, so it was chosen as the basis for the new ROUV.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] However, the AMETEK 2006 still required extensive improvements to meet the design team's goals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] One of the major upgrades was the redesign and incorporation of two manipulators that could operate around half a dozen tools.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] These manipulators were completed by the main subcontractor, the Huazhong University of Science and Technology (HUST), and eventually won 1st Place in the Scientific and Technological Advancement Award of the China Shipbuilding Industry Corporation in 1996 .
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] It was also one of the first ROUVs in the Chinese inventory to have a Tether Management System (TMS).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] The first 8A4 ROUV completed sea trials in 1993, operating at a depth of up to 600 meters, with a cruising radius of up to 150 meters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] During its evaluation, the 8A4 ROUV successfully opened a submarine compartment constructed of special steel, a feat no other ROUV in the Chinese inventory could achieve .
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] It subsequently entered service, and the 8A4 was thus dubbed the most capable salvage and rescue ROUV in Chinese service.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] In 1996, the 8A4 ROUV won 3rd Place in the Scientific and Technological Advancement Award of the China Shipbuilding Industry Corporation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Despite industry recognition and awards, the 8A4's deployment is limited due to financial constraints.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Except for the first unit, all the remaining 8A4 ROUVs have had their TMS removed due to the budget cuts, resulting in a significant reduction in performance, such as reducing the maximum operational depth by more than half .
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] It was not until the early 2010s that TMS was planned to be reintroduced to all the 8A4 ROUVs to achieve their full capabilities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Dragon Pearl (Long-Zhu, 龙珠)ROUV is a little known micro-ROUV designed specifically to work with the Jiaolong, operated by the Jiaolong's crew.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Therefore, the maximum operating depth of Dragon Pearl is equivalent to that of the Jiaolong.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Sea Crab (Hai-Xie, 海蟹 in Chinese) ROUV is an experimental ROUV developed from the experience gained from earlier ROUVs.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Sea Crab is different from previous ROUVs in that it walks on six legs to walk on the sea floor as a bottom crawler, rather than moving with propellers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Sea Crab was completed in 1984 and served mainly as a proof of concept unit, which lead to the development of later bottom crawler such as Sea Star described below.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Sea Pole (Hai-Ji, 海极) ROUV is a little-known remotely operated vehicle (ROV) developed from the 8A4 specifically for underwater explorations in polar regions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] It has been successfully deployed since the second Chinese Arctic expedition in 2003.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Based on experience gained from earlier Sea Crab bottom crawler, SIA jointly developed Sea Star (Hai-Xing, 海星) ROUV with Italian firm Sonsub.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] Equipped with two manipulators, Sea Star is a bottom crawler specifically designed for laying underwater cables on the seabed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/8a4-class-rouv] While they are grouped in the same family by their developer SIA and share many technologies, Sea Star 6000 is distinct from the original Sea Star in that it has a maximum depth of 6,000 meters and is designed for scientific research missions rather than commercial applications.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Between 1995 and 2003, *Kaikō* conducted more than 250 dives, collecting 350 biological species (including 180 different bacteria), some of which could prove to be useful in medical and industrial applications.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] *Kaikō* reached a maximum depth of 10,911.4 meters at the Challenger Deep on 24 March 1995, during its initial sea trials.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] *Kaikō* returned to Challenger Deep in February 1996, this time reaching a maximum depth of 10,898 meters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] *Kaikō* made its last visit to Challenger Deep in May 1998.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] On 29 May 2003, *Kaikō* was lost at sea off the coast of Shikoku Island during Typhoon Chan-Hom, when a steel secondary cable connecting it to its launcher at the ocean surface broke.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] In May 2004, JAMSTEC resumed its research operations, using a converted ROV as its vehicle.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] This ROV, formerly known as *UROV 7K*, was rechristened *Kaikō7000II*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The *7000* designation indicates that this vessel is rated for diving to a maximum depth of 7,000 meters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] RV *Kairei* (かいれい) is a deep sea research vessel that served as the support ship for *Kaikō*, and for its replacement ROV, *Kaikō7000II*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] It now serves as the support ship for *ABISMO*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] *Kairei* uses *ABISMO* to conduct surveys and observations of oceanic plateaus, abyssal plains, oceanic basins, submarine volcanoes, hydrothermal vents, oceanic trenches and other underwater terrain features to a maximum depth of 11,000 meters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] *Kairei* also conducts surveys of the structure of deep sub-bottoms with complicated geographical shapes in subduction zones using its on-board multi-channel reflection survey system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] While the temporary replacement ROV (*Kaikō7000II*) has a remarkable performance record, it is only rated to 7,000 meters and cannot reach the deepest oceanic trenches.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] For this reason, JAMSTEC engineers began work on a new 11,000-meter class of ROV in April 2005.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The project is called ***ABISMO*** (Automatic Bottom Inspection and Sampling Mobile), which translates to *abyss* in Spanish and Portuguese.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Except for the sampler and the smaller size of the ROV itself, the system configuration is the same as for *Kaikō*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The launcher launches and recovers the ROV along with its sampler.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Click here to see a photograph of *ABISMO* and its launcher, as well as RV *Kairei*, the support ship.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The lower part of the launcher is constructed of a stainless steel framework, within which the vehicle is stored.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Pressure hulls for electronic devices, a winch, a secondary cable drum and two electric transformers are located in the upper part of the launcher.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The samplers include a gravity core sampler and a bottom grab sampler.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] There is also a docking system and an acoustic positioning system in the lower part of the launcher.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The vehicle is hung in the launcher by the docking system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] When the system detaches it and the cable drum feeds the secondary cable, the vehicle can dive down, and its position is measured by the acoustic positioning system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The position of the launcher is measured by RV *Kairei*, the support ship.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The launcher also has a high-definition television (HDTV) camera with pan and tilt functions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Initial sea trials of *ABISMO* were conducted in 2007.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The craft successfully reached a planned depth of 9,760-meters, the deepest part of Izu–Ogasawara Trench, where it collected core samples of sediment from the seabed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Plans are underway for a mission to the Challenger Deep.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] In June 2008, the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology (JAMSTEC) deployed the 4,517-ton Deep Sea Research Vessel *Kairei* to the area of Guam for cruise KR08-05 Leg 1 and Leg 2.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] The 2-m long gravity core sampler was dropped in free fall, and sediment samples of 1.6m length were obtained.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Twelve bottles of water samples were also obtained at various depths..." ABISMO's dive #14 was into the TOTO caldera (12°42.7777 N, 143°32.4055 E), about 60 nmi northeast of the deepest waters of the *central* basin of the Challenger Deep, where they obtained videos of the hydrothermal plume.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Upon successful testing to 10,000 m (32,808 ft), JAMSTEC’ ROV *ABISMO* became, briefly, the only full-ocean-depth rated ROV in existence.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] On 31 May 2009, the ABISMO was joined by the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution's HROV *Nereus* as the only two operational full ocean depth capable remotely operated vehicles in existence.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] During the ROV *ABISMO's* deepest sea trails dive its manometer measured a depth of 10,257 m (33,652 ft) ±3 m (10 ft) in “Area 1” (vicinity of 12°43’ N, 143°33’ E).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/abismo] Leg 2, under chief scientist Takashi Murashima, operated at the Challenger Deep June 8–9, 2008, testing JAMSTEC's new full ocean depth “Free Fall Mooring System,” i.e. a lander.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] CO is a colorless and odorless gas which is initially non-irritating.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It is produced during incomplete burning of organic matter.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This can occur in cooking equipment, motor vehicles, or heaters which use carbon-based fuels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide primarily causes adverse effects by combining with hemoglobin to form carboxyhemoglobin (symbol COHb or HbCO), which prevents the blood from carrying oxygen and expelling carbon dioxide as carbaminohemoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Additionally, many other hemoproteins such as myoglobin, Cytochrome P450, and mitochondrial cytochrome oxidase are affected, along with other metallic and non-metallic cellular targets.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Diagnosis is typically based on a HbCO level of more than 3% among nonsmokers and more than 10% among smokers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The biological threshold for carboxyhemoglobin tolerance is typically accepted to be 15% COHb, meaning toxicity is consistently observed at levels in excess of this concentration.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The FDA has previously set a threshold of 14% COHb in certain clinical trials evaluating the therapeutic potential of carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In general, 30% COHb is considered severe carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The highest reported non-fatal carboxyhemoglobin level was 73% COHb.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Efforts to prevent poisoning include carbon monoxide detectors, proper venting of gas appliances, keeping chimneys clean, and keeping exhaust systems of vehicles in good repair.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Treatment of poisoning generally consists of giving 100% oxygen along with supportive care.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This procedure is often carried out until symptoms are absent and the HbCO level is less than 3%/10%.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide poisoning is relatively common, resulting in more than 20,000 emergency room visits a year in the United States.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It is the most common type of fatal poisoning in many countries.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In the United States, non-fire related cases result in more than 400 deaths a year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Poisonings occur more often in the winter, particularly from the use of portable generators during power outages.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The toxic effects of CO have been known since ancient history.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The discovery that hemoglobin is affected by CO emerged with an investigation by James Watt and Thomas Beddoes into the therapeutic potential of hydrocarbonate in 1793, and later confirmed by Claude Bernard between 1846 and 1857.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide is not toxic to all forms of life, and the toxicity is a classical dose-dependent example of hormesis.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Small amounts of carbon monoxide are naturally produced through many enzymatic and non-enzymatic reactions across phylogenetic kingdoms where it can serve as an important neurotransmitter (subcategorized as a gasotransmitter) and a potential therapeutic agent.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In the case of prokaryotes, some bacteria produce, consume and respond to carbon monoxide whereas certain other microbes are susceptible to its toxicity.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Currently, there are no known adverse effects on photosynthesizing plants.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Inhaling excessive concentrations of the gas can lead to hypoxic injury, nervous system damage, and even death.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] As pioneered by Esther Killick, different species and different people across diverse demographics may have different carbon monoxide tolerance levels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide is produced naturally by many physiologically relevant enzymatic and non-enzymatic reactions best exemplified by heme oxygenase catalyzing the biotransformation of heme (an iron protoporphyrin) into biliverdin and eventually bilirubin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Aside from physiological signaling, most carbon monoxide is stored as carboxyhemoglobin at non-toxic levels below 3% HbCO.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Small amounts of CO are beneficial and enzymes exist that produce it at times of oxidative stress.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] A variety of drugs are being developed to introduce small amounts of CO, these drugs are commonly called carbon monoxide-releasing molecules.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Historically, the therapeutic potential of factitious airs, notably carbon monoxide as hydrocarbonate, was investigated by Thomas Beddoes, James Watt, Tiberius Cavallo, James Lind, Humphry Davy, and others in many labs such as the Pneumatic Institution.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] On average, exposures at 100 ppm or greater is dangerous to human health.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The WHO recommended maximum levels of indoor CO exposure in 24 hours is 4 mg/m3 (3.5 ppm at 20 °C).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Acute exposure should not exceed 10 mg/m3 (8.7 ppm at 20 °C) in 8 hours, 35 mg/m3 (31 ppm at 20 °C) in one hour and 100 mg/m3 (87 ppm at 20 °C) in 15 minutes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The main manifestations of carbon monoxide poisoning develop in the organ systems most dependent on oxygen use, the central nervous system and the heart.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The initial symptoms of acute carbon monoxide poisoning include headache, nausea, malaise, and fatigue.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] These symptoms are often mistaken for a virus such as influenza or other illnesses such as food poisoning or gastroenteritis.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Headache is the most common symptom of acute carbon monoxide poisoning; it is often described as dull, frontal, and continuous.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Less common symptoms of acute carbon monoxide poisoning include myocardial ischemia, atrial fibrillation, pneumonia, pulmonary edema, high blood sugar, lactic acidosis, muscle necrosis, acute kidney failure, skin lesions, and visual and auditory problems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide exposure may lead to a significantly shorter life span due to heart damage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] One of the major concerns following acute carbon monoxide poisoning is the severe delayed neurological manifestations that may occur.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Problems may include difficulty with higher intellectual functions, short-term memory loss, dementia, amnesia, psychosis, irritability, a strange gait, speech disturbances, Parkinson's disease-like syndromes, cortical blindness, and a depressed mood.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Depression may occur in those who did not have pre-existing depression.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] These delayed neurological sequelae may occur in up to 50% of poisoned people after 2 to 40 days.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It is difficult to predict who will develop delayed sequelae; however, advanced age, loss of consciousness while poisoned, and initial neurological abnormalities may increase the chance of developing delayed symptoms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Chronic exposure to relatively low levels of carbon monoxide may cause persistent headaches, lightheadedness, depression, confusion, memory loss, nausea, hearing disorders and vomiting.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It is unknown whether low-level chronic exposure may cause permanent neurological damage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Typically, upon removal from exposure to carbon monoxide, symptoms usually resolve themselves, unless there has been an episode of severe acute poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] However, one case noted permanent memory loss and learning problems after a three-year exposure to relatively low levels of carbon monoxide from a faulty furnace.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Chronic exposure may worsen cardiovascular symptoms in some people.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Chronic carbon monoxide exposure might increase the risk of developing atherosclerosis.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Long-term exposures to carbon monoxide present the greatest risk to persons with coronary heart disease and in females who are pregnant.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In experimental animals, carbon monoxide appears to worsen noise-induced hearing loss at noise exposure conditions that would have limited effects on hearing otherwise.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In humans, hearing loss has been reported following carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Unlike the findings in animal studies, noise exposure was not a necessary factor for the auditory problems to occur.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] One classic sign of carbon monoxide poisoning is more often seen in the dead rather than the living – people have been described as looking red-cheeked and healthy.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] However, since this "cherry-red" appearance is more common in the dead, it is not considered a useful diagnostic sign in clinical medicine.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In autopsy examinations, the appearance of carbon monoxide poisoning is notable because unembalmed dead persons are normally bluish and pale, whereas dead carbon-monoxide poisoned people may appear unusually lifelike in coloration.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The colorant effect of carbon monoxide in such postmortem circumstances is thus analogous to its use as a red colorant in the commercial meat-packing industry.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The true number of cases of carbon monoxide poisoning is unknown, since many non-lethal exposures go undetected.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] From the available data, carbon monoxide poisoning is the most common cause of injury and death due to poisoning worldwide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Poisoning is typically more common during the winter months.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This is due to increased domestic use of gas furnaces, gas or kerosene space heaters, and kitchen stoves during the winter months, which if faulty and/or used without adequate ventilation, may produce excessive carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It has been estimated that more than 40,000 people per year seek medical attention for carbon monoxide poisoning in the United States.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] 95% of carbon monoxide poisoning deaths in Australia are due to gas space heaters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In many industrialized countries, carbon monoxide is the cause of more than 50% of fatal poisonings.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In the United States, approximately 200 people die each year from carbon monoxide poisoning associated with home fuel-burning heating equipment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide poisoning contributes to the approximately 5,613 smoke inhalation deaths each year in the United States.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] A report from New Zealand showed that 206 people died from carbon monoxide poisoning in the years of 2001 and 2002.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In total carbon monoxide poisoning was responsible for 43.9% of deaths by poisoning in that country.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In South Korea, 1,950 people had been poisoned by carbon monoxide with 254 deaths from 2001 through 2003.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] A report from Jerusalem showed 3.53 per 100,000 people were poisoned annually from 2001 through 2006.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In Hubei, China, 218 deaths from poisoning were reported over a 10-year period with 16.5% being from carbon monoxide exposure.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide is a product of combustion of organic matter under conditions of restricted oxygen supply, which prevents complete oxidation to carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Exposure typically occurs when equipment is used in buildings or semi-enclosed spaces.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Riding in the back of pickup trucks has led to poisoning in children.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Idling automobiles with the exhaust pipe blocked by snow has led to the poisoning of car occupants.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Any perforation between the exhaust manifold and shroud can result in exhaust gases reaching the cabin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Generators and propulsion engines on boats, notably houseboats, have resulted in fatal carbon monoxide exposures.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Poisoning may also occur following the use of a self-contained underwater breathing apparatus (SCUBA) due to faulty diving air compressors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In caves carbon monoxide can build up in enclosed chambers due to the presence of decomposing organic matter.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In coal mines incomplete combustion may occur during explosions resulting in the production of afterdamp.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The gas is up to 3% CO and may be fatal after just a single breath.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Following an explosion in a colliery, adjacent interconnected mines may become dangerous due to the afterdamp leaking from mine to mine.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Such an incident followed the Trimdon Grange explosion which killed men in the Kelloe mine.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Another source of poisoning is exposure to the organic solvent dichloromethane, also known as methylene chloride, found in some paint strippers, as the metabolism of dichloromethane produces carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In November 2019, an EPA ban on dichloromethane in paint strippers for consumer use took effect in the United States.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Prevention remains a vital public health issue, requiring public education on the safe operation of appliances, heaters, fireplaces, and internal-combustion engines, as well as increased emphasis on the installation of carbon monoxide detectors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide is tasteless, odourless, and colourless, and therefore can not be detected by visual cues or smell.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The United States Consumer Product Safety Commission has stated, "carbon monoxide detectors are as important to home safety as smoke detectors are", and recommends each home have at least one carbon monoxide detector, and preferably one on each level of the building.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] These devices, which are relatively inexpensive and widely available, are either battery- or AC-powered, with or without battery backup.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In buildings, carbon monoxide detectors are usually installed around heaters and other equipment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] If a relatively high level of carbon monoxide is detected, the device sounds an alarm, giving people the chance to evacuate and ventilate the building.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Unlike smoke detectors, carbon monoxide detectors do not need to be placed near ceiling level.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The use of carbon monoxide detectors has been standardized in many areas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In the US, NFPA 720–2009, the carbon monoxide detector guidelines published by the National Fire Protection Association, mandates the placement of carbon monoxide detectors/alarms on every level of the residence, including the basement, in addition to outside sleeping areas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In new homes, AC-powered detectors must have battery backup and be interconnected to ensure early warning of occupants at all levels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] NFPA 720-2009 is the first national carbon monoxide standard to address devices in non-residential buildings.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Gas organizations will often recommend getting gas appliances serviced at least once a year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The NFPA standard is not necessarily enforced by law.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] As of April 2006, the US state of Massachusetts requires detectors to be present in all residences with potential CO sources, regardless of building age and whether they are owner-occupied or rented.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This is enforced by municipal inspectors and was inspired by the death of 7-year-old Nicole Garofalo in 2005 due to snow blocking a home heating vent.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Other jurisdictions may have no requirement or only mandate detectors for new construction or at time of sale.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] As many symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning also occur with many other types of poisonings and infections (such as the flu), the diagnosis is often difficult.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] A history of potential carbon monoxide exposure, such as being exposed to a residential fire, may suggest poisoning, but the diagnosis is confirmed by measuring the levels of carbon monoxide in the blood.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This can be determined by measuring the amount of carboxyhemoglobin compared to the amount of hemoglobin in the blood.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The ratio of carboxyhemoglobin to hemoglobin molecules in an average person may be up to 5%, although cigarette smokers who smoke two packs per day may have levels up to 9%.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In symptomatic poisoned people they are often in the 10–30% range, while persons who die may have postmortem blood levels of 30–90%.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] As people may continue to experience significant symptoms of CO poisoning long after their blood carboxyhemoglobin concentration has returned to normal, presenting to examination with a normal carboxyhemoglobin level (which may happen in late states of poisoning) does not rule out poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide may be quantitated in blood using spectrophotometric methods or chromatographic techniques in order to confirm a diagnosis of poisoning in a person or to assist in the forensic investigation of a case of fatal exposure.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] A CO-oximeter can be used to determine carboxyhemoglobin levels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Pulse CO-oximeters estimate carboxyhemoglobin with a non-invasive finger clip similar to a pulse oximeter.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] These devices function by passing various wavelengths of light through the fingertip and measuring the light absorption of the different types of hemoglobin in the capillaries.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The use of a regular pulse oximeter is not effective in the diagnosis of carbon monoxide poisoning as these devices may be unable to distinguish carboxyhemoglobin from oxyhemoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Breath CO monitoring offers an alternative to pulse CO-oximetry.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carboxyhemoglobin levels have been shown to have a strong correlation with breath CO concentration.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] However, many of these devices require the user to inhale deeply and hold their breath to allow the CO in the blood to escape into the lung before the measurement can be made.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] As this is not possible in people who are unresponsive, these devices may not appropriate for use in on-scene emergency care detection of CO poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] There are many conditions to be considered in the differential diagnosis of carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The earliest symptoms, especially from low level exposures, are often non-specific and readily confused with other illnesses, typically flu-like viral syndromes, depression, chronic fatigue syndrome, chest pain, and migraine or other headaches.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide has been called a "great mimicker" due to the presentation of poisoning being diverse and nonspecific.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Other conditions included in the differential diagnosis include acute respiratory distress syndrome, altitude sickness, lactic acidosis, diabetic ketoacidosis, meningitis, methemoglobinemia, or opioid or toxic alcohol poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Initial treatment for carbon monoxide poisoning is to immediately remove the person from the exposure without endangering further people.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Those who are unconscious may require CPR on site.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Administering oxygen via non-rebreather mask shortens the half-life of carbon monoxide from 320 minutes, when breathing normal air, to only 80 minutes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Oxygen hastens the dissociation of carbon monoxide from carboxyhemoglobin, thus turning it back into hemoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Due to the possible severe effects in the baby, pregnant women are treated with oxygen for longer periods of time than non-pregnant people.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Hyperbaric oxygen is also used in the treatment of carbon monoxide poisoning, as it may hasten dissociation of CO from carboxyhemoglobin and cytochrome oxidase to a greater extent than normal oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Hyperbaric oxygen at three times atmospheric pressure reduces the half life of carbon monoxide to 23 minutes, compared to 80 minutes for oxygen at regular atmospheric pressure.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It may also enhance oxygen transport to the tissues by plasma, partially bypassing the normal transfer through hemoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] However, it is controversial whether hyperbaric oxygen actually offers any extra benefits over normal high flow oxygen, in terms of increased survival or improved long-term outcomes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] There have been randomized controlled trials in which the two treatment options have been compared; of the six performed, four found hyperbaric oxygen improved outcome and two found no benefit for hyperbaric oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Some of these trials have been criticized for apparent flaws in their implementation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] A review of all the literature concluded that the role of hyperbaric oxygen is unclear and the available evidence neither confirms nor denies a medically meaningful benefit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The authors suggested a large, well designed, externally audited, multicentre trial to compare normal oxygen with hyperbaric oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] While hyperbaric oxygen therapy is used for severe poisonings, the benefit over standard oxygen delivery is unclear.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Further treatment for other complications such as seizure, hypotension, cardiac abnormalities, pulmonary edema, and acidosis may be required.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Hypotension requires treatment with intravenous fluids; vasopressors may be required to treat myocardial depression.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Cardiac dysrhythmias are treated with standard advanced cardiac life support protocols.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] If severe, metabolic acidosis is treated with sodium bicarbonate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Treatment with sodium bicarbonate is controversial as acidosis may increase tissue oxygen availability.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Treatment of acidosis may only need to consist of oxygen therapy.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The delayed development of neuropsychiatric impairment is one of the most serious complications of carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Brain damage is confirmed following MRI or CAT scans.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Extensive follow up and supportive treatment is often required for delayed neurological damage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Outcomes are often difficult to predict following poisoning, especially people who have symptoms of cardiac arrest, coma, metabolic acidosis, or have high carboxyhemoglobin levels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] One study reported that approximately 30% of people with severe carbon monoxide poisoning will have a fatal outcome.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It has been reported that electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) may increase the likelihood of delayed neuropsychiatric sequelae (DNS) after carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] A device that also provides some carbon dioxide to stimulate faster breathing (sold under the brand name ClearMate) may also be used.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The precise mechanisms by which the effects of carbon monoxide are induced upon bodily systems are complex and not yet fully understood.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Known mechanisms include carbon monoxide binding to hemoglobin, myoglobin and mitochondrial cytochrome c oxidase and restricting oxygen supply, and carbon monoxide causing brain lipid peroxidation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide has a higher diffusion coefficient compared to oxygen, and the main enzyme in the human body that produces carbon monoxide is heme oxygenase, which is located in nearly all cells and platelets.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Most endogenously produced CO is stored bound to hemoglobin as carboxyhemoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The simplistic understanding for the mechanism of carbon monoxide toxicity is based on excess carboxyhemoglobin decreasing the oxygen-delivery capacity of the blood to tissues throughout the body.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In humans, the affinity between hemoglobin and carbon monoxide is approximately 240 times stronger than the affinity between hemoglobin and oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] However, certain mutations such as the Hb-Kirklareli mutation has a relative 80,000 times greater affinity for carbon monoxide than oxygen resulting in systemic carboxyhemoglobin reaching a sustained level of 16% COHb.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Hemoglobin is a tetramer with four prosthetic heme groups to serve as oxygen binding sites.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The average red blood cell contains 250 million hemoglobin molecules, therefore 1 billion heme sites capable of binding gas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Delivery of oxygen is largely driven by the Bohr effect and Haldane effect.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Furthermore, the mechanism for formation of carbaminohemoglobin generates additional 'acidic' hydrogen ions that may further stabilize the protonated/ionized deoxygenated hemoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide is not 'ejected' due to acid, therefore carbon monoxide poisoning disturbs this physiological process hence the venous blood of poisoning patients is bright red akin to arterial blood since the carbonyl/carbon monoxide is retained.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide also binds to the hemeprotein myoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] It has a high affinity for myoglobin, about 60 times greater than that of oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide bound to myoglobin may impair its ability to utilize oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This causes reduced cardiac output and hypotension, which may result in brain ischemia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] A delayed return of symptoms have been reported.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This results following a recurrence of increased carboxyhemoglobin levels; this effect may be due to a late release of carbon monoxide from myoglobin, which subsequently binds to hemoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Another mechanism involves effects on the mitochondrial respiratory enzyme chain that is responsible for effective tissue utilization of oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide binds to cytochrome oxidase with less affinity than oxygen, so it is possible that it requires significant intracellular hypoxia before binding.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This binding interferes with aerobic metabolism and efficient adenosine triphosphate synthesis.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Cells respond by switching to anaerobic metabolism, causing anoxia, lactic acidosis, and eventual cell death.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The rate of dissociation between carbon monoxide and cytochrome oxidase is slow, causing a relatively prolonged impairment of oxidative metabolism.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The mechanism that is thought to have a significant influence on delayed effects involves formed blood cells and chemical mediators, which cause brain lipid peroxidation (degradation of unsaturated fatty acids).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide causes endothelial cell and platelet release of nitric oxide, and the formation of oxygen free radicals including peroxynitrite.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In the brain this causes further mitochondrial dysfunction, capillary leakage, leukocyte sequestration, and apoptosis.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The result of these effects is lipid peroxidation, which causes delayed reversible demyelination of white matter in the central nervous system known as Grinker myelinopathy, which can lead to edema and necrosis within the brain.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This brain damage occurs mainly during the recovery period.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This may result in cognitive defects, especially affecting memory and learning, and movement disorders.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] These disorders are typically related to damage to the cerebral white matter and basal ganglia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Hallmark pathological changes following poisoning are bilateral necrosis of the white matter, globus pallidus, cerebellum, hippocampus and the cerebral cortex.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide poisoning in pregnant women may cause severe adverse fetal effects.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Poisoning causes fetal tissue hypoxia by decreasing the release of maternal oxygen to the fetus.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide also crosses the placenta and combines with fetal hemoglobin, causing more direct fetal tissue hypoxia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Additionally, fetal hemoglobin has a 10 to 15% higher affinity for carbon monoxide than adult hemoglobin, causing more severe poisoning in the fetus than in the adult.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Elimination of carbon monoxide is slower in the fetus, leading to an accumulation of the toxic chemical.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The level of fetal morbidity and mortality in acute carbon monoxide poisoning is significant, so despite mild maternal poisoning or following maternal recovery, severe fetal poisoning or death may still occur.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Humans have maintained a complex relationship with carbon monoxide since first learning to control fire circa 800,000 BC.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Primitive cavemen probably discovered the toxicity of carbon monoxide upon introducing fire into their dwellings.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The early development of metallurgy and smelting technologies emerging circa 6,000 BC through the Bronze Age likewise plagued humankind with carbon monoxide exposure.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Apart from the toxicity of carbon monoxide, indigenous Native Americans may have experienced the neuroactive properties of carbon monoxide through shamanistic fireside rituals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Early civilizations developed mythological tales to explain the origin of fire, such as Vulcan, Pkharmat, and Prometheus from Greek mythology who shared fire with humans.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Aristotle (384–322 BC) first recorded that burning coals produced toxic fumes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Greek physician Galen (129–199 AD) speculated that there was a change in the composition of the air that caused harm when inhaled, and symptoms of CO poisoning appeared in Cassius Iatrosophista's *Quaestiones Medicae et Problemata Naturalia* circa 130 AD.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Julian the Apostate, Caelius Aurelianus, and several others similarly documented early knowledge of the toxicity symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning as caused by coal fumes in the ancient era.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Documented cases by Livy and Cicero allude to carbon monoxide being used as a method of suicide in ancient Rome.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Emperor Lucius Verus used smoke to execute prisoners.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Many deaths have been linked to carbon monoxide poisoning including Emperor Jovian, Empress Fausta, and Seneca.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The most high-profile death by carbon monoxide poisoning may possibly have been Cleopatra or Edgar Allan Poe.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Georg Ernst Stahl mentioned *carbonarii halitus* in 1697 in reference to toxic vapors thought to be carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Friedrich Hoffmann conducted the first modern scientific investigation into carbon monoxide poisoning from coal in 1716, notably rejecting villagers attributing death to demonic superstition.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Herman Boerhaave conducted the first scientific experiments on the effect of carbon monoxide (coal fumes) on animals in the 1730s.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Joseph Priestley is credited with first synthesizing carbon monoxide in 1772 which he had called heavy inflammable air, and Carl Wilhelm Scheele isolated carbon monoxide from coal in 1773 suggesting it to be the toxic entity.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The dose-dependent risk of carbon monoxide poisoning as hydrocarbonate was investigated in the late 1790s by Thomas Beddoes, James Watt, Tiberius Cavallo, James Lind, Humphry Davy, and many others in the context of inhalation of factitious airs, much of which occurred at the Pneumatic Institution.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] William Cruickshank discovered carbon monoxide as a molecule containing one carbon and one oxygen atom in 1800, thereby initiating the modern era of research exclusively focused on carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The mechanism for toxicity was first suggested by James Watt in 1793, followed by Adrien Chenot in 1854 and finally demonstrated by Claude Bernard after 1846 as published in 1857 and also independently published by Felix Hoppe-Seyler in the same year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The first controlled clinical trial studying the toxicity of carbon monoxide occurred in 1973.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Carbon monoxide poisoning has plagued coal miners for many centuries.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In the context of mining, carbon monoxide is widely known as whitedamp.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] John Scott Haldane identified carbon monoxide as the lethal constituent of afterdamp, the gas created by combustion, after examining many bodies of miners killed in pit explosions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] By 1911, Haldane introduced the use of small animals for miners to detect dangerous levels of carbon monoxide underground, either white mice or canaries which have little tolerance for carbon monoxide thereby offering an early warning, i.e. canary in a coal mine.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The canary in British pits was replaced in 1986 by the electronic gas detector.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The first qualitative analytical method to detect carboxyhemoglobin emerged in 1858 with a colorimetric method developed by Felix Hoppe-Seyler, and the first quantitative analysis method emerged in 1880 with Josef von Fodor.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The use of oxygen emerged with anecdotal reports such as Humphry Davy having been treated with oxygen in 1799 upon inhaling three quarts of hydrocarbonate (water gas).
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Samuel Witter developed an oxygen inhalation protocol in response to carbon monoxide poisoning in 1814.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Similarly, an oxygen inhalation protocol was recommend for malaria (literally translated to "bad air") in 1830 based on malaria symptoms aligning with carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Other oxygen protocols emerged in the late 1800s.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The use of hyperbaric oxygen in rats following poisoning was studied by Haldane in 1895 while its use in humans began in the 1960s.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The worst accidental mass poisoning from carbon monoxide was the Balvano train disaster which occurred on 3 March 1944 in Italy, when a freight train with many illegal passengers stalled in a tunnel, leading to the death of over 500 people.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Over 50 people are suspected to have died from smoke inhalation as a result of the Branch Davidian Massacre during the Waco siege in 1993.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] On 14 December 2024 12 individuals died by carbon monoxide poisoning in Gudauri (Georgia) as electric generators using fuel oil were placed in a closed area near their rooms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In ancient history, Hannibal executed Roman prisoners with coal fumes during the Second Punic War.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The extermination of stray dogs by a carbon monoxide gas chamber was described in 1874.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] In 1884, an article appeared in *Scientific American* describing the use of a carbon monoxide gas chamber for slaughterhouse operations as well as euthanizing a variety of animals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] As part of the Holocaust during World War II, the Nazis used gas vans at Chelmno extermination camp and elsewhere to murder an estimated 700,000 or more people by carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] This method was also used in the gas chambers of several death camps such as Treblinka, Sobibor, and Belzec.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Gassing with carbon monoxide started in Action T4.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] The gas was supplied by IG Farben in pressurized cylinders and fed by tubes into the gas chambers built at various mental hospitals, such as Hartheim Euthanasia Centre.
[src:carbon-monoxide-poisoning/carbon-monoxide-poisoning] Exhaust fumes from tank engines, for example, were used to supply the gas to the chambers.
